sec.p:
Recently, Orthochromis indermauri has been described from the lower reaches of the Lufubu River, where it appears to be endemic. Interestingly, it represents a different ancient mitochondrial haplotype lineage within the megadiverse
Haplochromini (
Schedel et al . 2019
)
. Lufubuchromis relictus is the second endemic cichlid species described from the Lufubu but appears to be restricted to the upper reaches of the Lufubu and its tributaries. Furthermore, there are at least two undescribed cichlid species present in the Lufubu drainage system, Telmatochromis sp. “Lufubu”, restricted to the lower reaches of the Lufubu ( Indermaur 2014 ), and Serranochromis sp. “Lufubu”, currently documented only from a single location in the upper reaches of the Lufubu River (
Koblmüller et al . 2012
). The striking difference in the ichthyofaunal composition of the Upper and Lower Lufubu River has been suggested to be the result of several cascades and waterfalls prohibiting upstream and, possibly, downstream migration, which could explain the absence of Lufubuchromis in the lower reaches of the river (
Koblmüller et al . 2012
).
